[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] In mathematics, the **Dedekind eta function**, named after Richard Dedekind, is a modular form of weight 1/2 and is a function defined on the upper half-plane of complex numbers, where the imaginary part is positive.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] It also occurs in bosonic string theory.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The presence of 24 can be understood by connection with other occurrences, such as in the 24-dimensional Leech lattice.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The eta function is holomorphic on the upper half-plane but cannot be continued analytically beyond it.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] In the second equation the branch of the square root is chosen such that √−*iτ* = 1 when *τ* = *i*.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] is a transformation belonging to the modular group.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] We may assume that either *c* > 0, or *c* = 0 and *d* = 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Because of these functional equations the eta function is a modular form of weight ⁠1/2⁠ and level 1 for a certain character of order 24 of the metaplectic double cover of the modular group, and can be used to define other modular forms.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Some authors omit the factor of (2*π*)12, so that the series expansion has integral coefficients.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] This can be proved by using $x=2\pi i\tau$ in Euler Pentagonal number theorem with the definition of eta function.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Because the eta function is easy to compute numerically from either power series, it is often helpful in computation to express other functions in terms of it when possible, and products and quotients of eta functions, called eta quotients, can be used to express a great variety of modular forms.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The picture on this page shows the modulus of the Euler function: the additional factor of *q*⁠1/24⁠ between this and eta makes almost no visual difference whatsoever.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Thus, this picture can be taken as a picture of eta as a function of q.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The theory of the algebraic characters of the affine Lie algebras gives rise to a large class of previously unknown identities for the eta function.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] These identities follow from the Weyl–Kac character formula, and more specifically from the so-called "denominator identities".
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The characters themselves allow the construction of generalizations of the Jacobi theta function which transform under the modular group; this is what leads to the identities.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] where *q* = *e*2*πiτ* is the q-analog or "deformation" of the highest weight of a module.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] where d is a non-negative integer and rd is any integer.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Linear combinations of eta quotients at imaginary quadratic arguments may be algebraic, while combinations of eta quotients may even be integral.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] with the 24th power of the Weber modular function 𝔣(*τ*).
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] and so on, values which appear in Ramanujan–Sato series.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Eta quotients may also be a useful tool for describing bases of modular forms, which are difficult to compute and express directly.
