[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] These results lead to several characterizations of spaces of modular forms that can be spanned by modular eta quotients.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Using the graded ring structure on the ring of modular forms, we can compute bases of vector spaces of modular forms composed of $\mathbb {C}$ -linear combinations of eta-quotients.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] For example, if we assume *N* = *pq* is a semiprime then the following process can be used to compute an eta-quotient basis of *Mk*(Γ0(*N*)).
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Compute the dimension D of *Mk*(Γ0(*N*)).
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] This tells us how many linearly-independent modular eta quotients we will need to compute to form a basis.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Reduce the number of eta quotients to consider.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] For semiprimes we can reduce the number of partitions using the bound on $\sum _{0<d\mid N}|r_{d}|$ and by noticing that the sum of the orders of vanishing at the cusps of Γ0(*N*) must equal $S:={\frac {(p+1)(q+1)}{6}}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Find all partitions of S into 4-tuples (there are 4 cusps of Γ0(*N*)), and among these consider only the partitions which satisfy Newman's conditions (we can convert orders of vanishing into exponents).
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Each of these partitions corresponds to a unique eta quotient.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Determine the minimum number of terms in the q-expansion of each eta quotient required to identify elements uniquely (this uses a result known as Sturm's bound).
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Then use linear algebra to determine a maximal independent set among these eta quotients.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Assuming that we have not already found D linearly independent eta quotients, find an appropriate vector space *M**k*′(Γ0(*N*)) such that *k*′ and *M**k*′(Γ0(*N*)) is spanned by (weakly holomorphic) eta quotients, and *M**k*′−*k*(Γ0(*N*)) contains an eta quotient ηg.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] Take a modular form f with weight k that is not in the span of our computed eta quotients, and compute *f* *ηg* as a linear combination of eta-quotients in *M**k*′(Γ0(*N*)) and then divide out by ηg.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] The result will be an expression of f as a linear combination of eta quotients as desired.
[src:elliptic-functions/dedekind-eta-function] A collection of over 6300 product identities for the Dedekind eta function in a canonical, standardized form is available at the Wayback machine of Michael Somos' website.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] In the mathematical field of complex analysis, **elliptic functions** are special kinds of meromorphic functions, that satisfy two periodicity conditions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] They are named elliptic functions because they come from elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Those integrals are in turn named elliptic because they first were encountered for the calculation of the arc length of an ellipse.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Important elliptic functions are Jacobi elliptic functions and the Weierstrass $\wp$ -function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Further development of this theory led to hyperelliptic functions and modular forms.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] So elliptic functions have two periods and are therefore doubly periodic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] for every linear combination $\gamma =m\omega _{1}+n\omega _{2}$ with $m,n\in \mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] is a *fundamental domain* of $\Lambda$ acting on $\mathbb {C}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Geometrically the complex plane is tiled with parallelograms.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Everything that happens in one fundamental domain repeats in all the others.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] For that reason we can view elliptic function as functions with the quotient group $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ as their domain.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] This quotient group, called an elliptic curve, can be visualised as a parallelogram where opposite sides are identified, which topologically is a torus.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] A holomorphic elliptic function is constant.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] This is the original form of Liouville's theorem and can be derived from it.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] A holomorphic elliptic function is bounded since it takes on all of its values on the fundamental domain which is compact.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] So it is constant by Liouville's theorem.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Every elliptic function has finitely many poles in $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ and the sum of its residues is zero.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] This theorem implies that there is no elliptic function not equal to zero with exactly one pole of order one or exactly one zero of order one in the fundamental domain.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] A non-constant elliptic function takes on every value the same number of times in $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ counted with multiplicity.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] One of the most important elliptic functions is the Weierstrass $\wp$ -function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] It is constructed in such a way that it has a pole of order two at every lattice point.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] The term $-{\frac {1}{\lambda ^{2}}}$ is there to make the series convergent.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] $\wp$ is an even elliptic function; that is, $\wp (-z)=\wp (z)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] One of the main results of the theory of elliptic functions is the following: Every elliptic function with respect to a given period lattice $\Lambda$ can be expressed as a rational function in terms of $\wp$ and $\wp '$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] where $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ are constants that depend on $\Lambda$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] where the isomorphism maps $\wp$ to X and $\wp '$ to Y .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] The relation to elliptic integrals has mainly a historical background.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Elliptic integrals had been studied by Legendre, whose work was taken on by Niels Henrik Abel and Carl Gustav Jacobi.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] After continuation to the complex plane they turned out to be doubly periodic and are known as Abel elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Jacobi elliptic functions are similarly obtained as inverse functions of elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] and inverted it: $x=\operatorname {sn} (\xi )$ . $\operatorname {sn}$ stands for *sinus amplitudinis* and is the name of the new function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Only by taking this step, Jacobi could prove his general transformation formula of elliptic integrals in 1827.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Shortly after the development of infinitesimal calculus the theory of elliptic functions was started by the Italian mathematician Giulio di Fagnano and the Swiss mathematician Leonhard Euler.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] When they tried to calculate the arc length of a lemniscate they encountered problems involving integrals that contained the square root of polynomials of degree 3 and 4.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] It was clear that those so called elliptic integrals could not be solved using elementary functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Fagnano observed an algebraic relation between elliptic integrals, what he published in 1750.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Euler immediately generalized Fagnano's results and posed his algebraic addition theorem for elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Except for a comment by Landen his ideas were not pursued until 1786, when Legendre published his paper *Mémoires sur les intégrations par arcs d’ellipse*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Legendre subsequently studied elliptic integrals and called them *elliptic functions*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Legendre introduced a three-fold classification – three kinds – which was a crucial simplification of the rather complicated theory at that time.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Other important works of Legendre are: *Mémoire sur les transcendantes elliptiques* (1792), *Exercices de calcul intégral* (1811–1817), *Traité des fonctions elliptiques* (1825–1832).
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Legendre's work was mostly left untouched by mathematicians until 1826.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Subsequently, Niels Henrik Abel and Carl Gustav Jacobi resumed the investigations and quickly discovered new results.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] At first they inverted the elliptic integral function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Following a suggestion of Jacobi in 1829 these inverse functions are now called *elliptic functions*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] One of Jacobi's most important works is *Fundamenta nova theoriae functionum ellipticarum* which was published 1829.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] The addition theorem Euler found was posed and proved in its general form by Abel in 1829.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] In those days the theory of elliptic functions and the theory of doubly periodic functions were considered to be different theories.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] They were brought together by Briot and Bouquet in 1856.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-function] Gauss discovered many of the properties of elliptic functions 30 years earlier but never published anything on the subject.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In integral calculus, an **elliptic integral** is one of a number of related functions defined as the value of certain integrals, which were first studied by Giulio Fagnano and Leonhard Euler (c.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Their name originates from their connection with the problem of finding the arc length of an ellipse.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] where *R* is a rational function of its two arguments, *P* is a polynomial of degree 3 or 4 with no repeated roots, and *c* is a constant.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In general, integrals in this form cannot be expressed in terms of elementary functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Exceptions to this general rule are when *P* has repeated roots, when *R*(*x*, *y*) contains no odd powers of *y*, and when the integral is pseudo-elliptic.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] However, with the appropriate reduction formula, every elliptic integral can be brought into a form that involves integrals over rational functions and the three Legendre canonical forms, also known as the elliptic integrals of the first, second and third kind.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Besides the Legendre form given below, the elliptic integrals may also be expressed in Carlson symmetric form.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Additional insight into the theory of the elliptic integral may be gained through the study of the Schwarz–Christoffel mapping.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Historically, elliptic functions were discovered as inverse functions of elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Each of the above three quantities is completely determined by any of the others (given that they are non-negative).
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The other argument can likewise be expressed as *φ*, the *amplitude*, or as *x* or *u*, where *x* = sin *φ* = sn *u* and sn is one of the Jacobian elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Specifying the value of any one of these quantities determines the others.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The latter is sometimes called the *delta amplitude* and written as Δ(*φ*) = dn *u*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Sometimes the literature also refers to the *complementary parameter*, the *complementary modulus,* or the *complementary modular angle*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] These are further defined in the article on quarter periods.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In this notation, the use of a vertical bar as delimiter indicates that the argument following it is the "parameter" (as defined above), while the backslash indicates that it is the modular angle.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] There are still other conventions for the notation of elliptic integrals employed in the literature.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The notation with interchanged arguments, *F*(*k*, *φ*), is often encountered; and similarly *E*(*k*, *φ*) for the integral of the second kind.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Abramowitz and Stegun substitute the integral of the first kind, *F*(*φ*, *k*), for the argument φ in their definition of the integrals of the second and third kinds, unless this argument is followed by a vertical bar: i.e.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Moreover, their complete integrals employ the *parameter* *k*2 as argument in place of the modulus *k*, i.e.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] And the integral of the third kind defined by Gradshteyn and Ryzhik, Π(*φ*, *n*, *k*), puts the amplitude φ first and not the "characteristic" n.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Thus one must be careful with the notation when using these functions, because various reputable references and software packages use different conventions in the definitions of the elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] For example, Wolfram's Mathematica software and Wolfram Alpha define the complete elliptic integral of the first kind in terms of the parameter *m*, instead of the elliptic modulus *k*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] With *x* = sn(*u*, *k*) one has: $F(x;k)=u;$ demonstrating that this Jacobian elliptic function is a simple inverse of the incomplete elliptic integral of the first kind.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The meridian arc length from the equator to latitude *φ* is written in terms of *E*: $m(\varphi )=a\left(E(\varphi ,e)+{\frac {d^{2}}{d\varphi ^{2}}}E(\varphi ,e)\right),$ where *a* is the semi-major axis, and *e* is the eccentricity.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The number *n* is called the **characteristic** and can take on any value, independently of the other arguments.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Note though that the value Π(1; ⁠π/2⁠ | *m*) is infinite, for any *m*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Elliptic Integrals are said to be 'complete' when the amplitude *φ* = ⁠π/2⁠ and therefore *x* = 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] where *n*!! denotes the double factorial.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The complete elliptic integral of the first kind is sometimes called the quarter period.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] If *k*2 = *λ*(*i*√*r*) and $r\in \mathbb {Q} ^{+}$ (where λ is the modular lambda function), then *K*(*k*) is expressible in closed form in terms of the gamma function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] More generally, the condition that ${\frac {iK'}{K}}={\frac {iK\left({\sqrt {1-k^{2}}}\right)}{K(k)}}$ be in an imaginary quadratic field is sufficient.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Keeping only the first two terms is correct to 0.01 precision for *k* < ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] A second solution to this equation is $K\left({\sqrt {1-k^{2}}}\right)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Here, we use the complete elliptic integral of the first kind with the *parameter* m instead, because the squaring function introduces problems when inverting in the complex plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The equation $\tau =i{\frac {K[1-m]}{K[m]}}$ can then be solved (provided that a solution m exists) by $m={\frac {\theta _{2}(\tau )^{4}}{\theta _{3}(\tau )^{4}}}$ which is in fact the modular lambda function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] For an ellipse with semi-major axis *a* and semi-minor axis *b* and eccentricity *e* = √1 − *b*2/*a*2, the complete elliptic integral of the second kind *E*(*e*) is equal to one quarter of the circumference *C* of the ellipse measured in units of the semi-major axis *a*.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Like the integral of the first kind, the complete elliptic integral of the second kind can be computed very efficiently using the arithmetic–geometric mean.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In practice, the arithmetic-geometric mean would simply be computed up to some limit.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] This formula converges quadratically for all |*k*| ≤ 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] To speed up computation further, the relation *c**n* + 1 = ⁠*cn*2/4*a**n* + 1⁠ can be used.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Just like the complete elliptic integrals of the first and second kind, the complete elliptic integral of the third kind can be computed very efficiently using the arithmetic-geometric mean.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In 1829, Jacobi defined the **Jacobi zeta function**: $Z(\varphi ,k)=E(\varphi ,k)-{\frac {E(k)}{K(k)}}F(\varphi ,k).$ It is periodic in $\varphi$ with minimal period $\pi$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] It is related to the Jacobi zn function by $Z(\varphi ,k)=\operatorname {zn} (F(\varphi ,k),k)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Whittaker and Watson (1927)), sometimes Z means Wikipedia's $\operatorname {zn}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] King (1924)) use Z for both Wikipedia's Z and $\operatorname {zn}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] The Legendre's relation for tangential modular counterparts results directly from the Legendre's identity for Pythagorean modular counterparts by using the Landen modular transformation on the Pythagorean counter modulus.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] For the lemniscatic case, the elliptic modulus or specific eccentricity ε is equal to half the square root of two.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Now the modular general case is worked out.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] For this purpose, the derivatives of the complete elliptic integrals are derived after the modulus $\varepsilon$ and then they are combined.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] And then the Legendre's identity balance is determined.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Legendre's identity includes products of any two complete elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] In relation to the $\varepsilon$ the equation balance constantly gives the value zero.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] Because if the derivative of a continuous function constantly takes the value zero, then the concerned function is a constant function.
[src:elliptic-functions/elliptic-integral] This means that this function results in the same function value for each abscissa value $\varepsilon$ and the associated function graph is therefore a horizontal straight line.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In mathematics, the **Jacobi elliptic functions** are a set of basic elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] They are found in the description of the motion of a pendulum, as well as in the design of electronic elliptic filters.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] While trigonometric functions are defined with reference to a circle, the Jacobi elliptic functions are a generalization which refer to other conic sections, the ellipse in particular.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The relation to trigonometric functions is contained in the notation, for example, by the matching notation $\operatorname {sn}$ for $\sin$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The Jacobi elliptic functions are used more often in practical problems than the Weierstrass elliptic functions as they do not require notions of complex analysis to be defined and/or understood.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] They were introduced by Carl Gustav Jakob Jacobi (1829).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Carl Friedrich Gauss had already studied special Jacobi elliptic functions in 1797, the lemniscate elliptic functions in particular, but his work was published much later.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] There are twelve Jacobi elliptic functions denoted by $\operatorname {pq} (u,m)$ , where $\mathrm {p}$ and $\mathrm {q}$ are any of the letters $\mathrm {c}$ , $\mathrm {s}$ , $\mathrm {n}$ , and $\mathrm {d}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] (Functions of the form $\operatorname {pp} (u,m)$ are trivially set to unity for notational completeness.) u is the argument, and m is the parameter, both of which may be complex.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In fact, the Jacobi elliptic functions are meromorphic in both u and m .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The distribution of the zeros and poles in the u -plane is well-known.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] However, questions of the distribution of the zeros and poles in the m -plane remain to be investigated.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the complex plane of the argument u , the twelve functions form a repeating lattice of simple poles and zeroes.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Depending on the function, one repeating parallelogram, or unit cell, will have sides of length $2K$ or $4K$ on the real axis, and $2K'$ or $4K'$ on the imaginary axis, where $K=K(m)$ and $K'=K(1-m)$ are known as the quarter periods with $K(\cdot )$ being the elliptic integral of the first kind.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The nature of the unit cell can be determined by inspecting the "auxiliary rectangle" (generally a parallelogram), which is a rectangle formed by the origin $(0,0)$ at one corner, and $(K,K')$ as the diagonally opposite corner.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] As in the diagram, the four corners of the auxiliary rectangle are named $\mathrm {s}$ , $\mathrm {c}$ , $\mathrm {d}$ , and $\mathrm {n}$ , going counter-clockwise from the origin.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The function $\operatorname {pq} (u,m)$ will have a zero at the $\mathrm {p}$ corner and a pole at the $\mathrm {q}$ corner.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The twelve functions correspond to the twelve ways of arranging these poles and zeroes in the corners of the rectangle.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When the argument u and parameter m are real, with $0<m<1$ , K and $K'$ will be real and the auxiliary parallelogram will in fact be a rectangle, and the Jacobi elliptic functions will all be real valued on the real line.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Since the Jacobi elliptic functions are doubly periodic in u , they factor through a torus – in effect, their domain can be taken to be a torus, just as cosine and sine are in effect defined on a circle.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Instead of having only one circle, we now have the product of two circles, one real and the other imaginary.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The complex plane can be replaced by a complex torus.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The circumference of the first circle is $4K$ and the second $4K'$ , where K and $K'$ are the quarter periods.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Each function has two zeroes and two poles at opposite positions on the torus.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Among the points 0 , K , $K+iK'$ , $iK'$ there is one zero and one pole.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] , illustrating their double periodic behavior.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The elliptic functions can be given in a variety of notations, which can make the subject unnecessarily confusing.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Elliptic functions are functions of two variables.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The first variable might be given in terms of the **amplitude** $\varphi$ , or more commonly, in terms of u given below.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The second variable might be given in terms of the **parameter** m , or as the **elliptic modulus** k , where $k^{2}=m$ , or in terms of the **modular angle** $\alpha$ , where $m=\sin ^{2}\alpha$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The complements of k and m are defined as $m'=1-m$ and ${\textstyle k'={\sqrt {m'}}}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] These four terms are used below without comment to simplify various expressions.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The twelve Jacobi elliptic functions are generally written as $\operatorname {pq} (u,m)$ where $\mathrm {p}$ and $\mathrm {q}$ are any of the letters $\mathrm {c}$ , $\mathrm {s}$ , $\mathrm {n}$ , and $\mathrm {d}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Functions of the form $\operatorname {pp} (u,m)$ are trivially set to unity for notational completeness.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Throughout this article, $\operatorname {pq} (u,t^{2})=\operatorname {pq} (u;t)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] There is a definition, relating the elliptic functions to the inverse of the incomplete elliptic integral of the first kind F .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] These functions take the parameters u and m as inputs.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The remaining nine elliptic functions are easily built from the above three ( $\operatorname {sn}$ , $\operatorname {cn}$ , $\operatorname {dn}$ ), and are given in a section below.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Note that when $\varphi =\pi /2$ , that u then equals the quarter period K .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the most general setting, $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ is a multivalued function (in u ) with infinitely many logarithmic branch points (the branches differ by integer multiples of $2\pi$ ), namely the points $2sK(m)+(4t+1)K(1-m)i$ and $2sK(m)+(4t+3)K(1-m)i$ where $s,t\in \mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In contrast, $\sin \operatorname {am} (u|m)$ and other elliptic functions have no branch points, give consistent values for every branch of $\operatorname {am}$ , and are meromorphic in the whole complex plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Since every elliptic function is meromorphic in the whole complex plane (by definition), $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ (when considered as a single-valued function) is not an elliptic function.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] However, a particular cutting for $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ can be made in the u -plane by line segments from $2sK(m)+(4t+1)K(1-m)i$ to $2sK(m)+(4t+3)K(1-m)i$ with $s,t\in \mathbb {Z}$ ; then it only remains to define $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ at the branch cuts by continuity from some direction.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Then $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ becomes single-valued and singly-periodic in u with the minimal period $4iK(1-m)$ and it has singularities at the logarithmic branch points mentioned above.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] If $m\in \mathbb {R}$ and $m\leq 1$ , $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ is continuous in u on the real line.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When $m>1$ , the branch cuts of $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ in the u -plane cross the real line at $2(2s+1)K(1/m)/{\sqrt {m}}$ for $s\in \mathbb {Z}$ ; therefore for $m>1$ , $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ is not continuous in u on the real line and jumps by $2\pi$ on the discontinuities.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] But defining $\operatorname {am} (u|m)$ this way gives rise to very complicated branch cuts in the m -plane (*not* the u -plane); they have not been fully described as of yet.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Let $E(\varphi |m)=\int _{0}^{\varphi }{\sqrt {1-m\sin ^{2}\theta }}\,\mathrm {d} \theta$ be the incomplete elliptic integral of the second kind with parameter m .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Then the **Jacobi epsilon** function can be defined as ${\mathcal {E}}(u|m)=E(\operatorname {am} (u|m)|m)$ for $u\in \mathbb {R}$ and $0<m<1$ and by analytic continuation in each of the variables otherwise: the Jacobi epsilon function is meromorphic in the whole complex plane (in both u and m ).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Alternatively, throughout both the u -plane and m -plane, ${\mathcal {E}}(u|m)=\int _{0}^{u}\operatorname {dn} ^{2}(t|m)\,\mathrm {d} t;$ ${\mathcal {E}}$ is well-defined in this way because all residues of $t\mapsto \operatorname {dn} (t|m)^{2}$ are zero, so the integral is path-independent.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The **Jacobi zn** function is defined by $\operatorname {zn} (u|m)={\mathcal {E}}(u|m)-{\frac {E(m)}{K(m)}}u.$ It is a singly periodic function which is meromorphic in u , but not in m (due to the branch cuts of E and K ).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Historically, the Jacobi elliptic functions were first defined by using the amplitude.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In more modern texts on elliptic functions, the Jacobi elliptic functions are defined by other means, for example by ratios of theta functions (see below), and the amplitude is ignored.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In modern terms, the relation to elliptic integrals would be expressed by $\operatorname {sn} (F(\varphi |m)|m)=\sin \varphi$ (or $\operatorname {cn} (F(\varphi |m)|m)=\cos \varphi$ ) instead of $\operatorname {am} (F(\varphi |m)|m)=\varphi$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] $\cos \varphi ,\,\sin \varphi$ are defined on the unit circle with radius $r=1$ and angle $\varphi =$ arc length of the unit circle measured from the positive *x*-axis.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Similarly, Jacobi elliptic functions are defined on the unit ellipse with $a=1$ and $b\geq 1$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] For each angle $\varphi$ the parameter $u=u(\varphi ,m)=\int _{0}^{\varphi }r(\theta ,m)\,d\theta$ (the incomplete elliptic integral of the first kind) is computed.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] On the unit circle ( $a=b=1$ ), u would be an arc length.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] However, the relation of u to the arc length of an ellipse is more complicated.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Let $P=(x,y)=(r\cos \varphi ,r\sin \varphi )$ be a point on the ellipse, and let $P'=(x',y')=(\cos \varphi ,\sin \varphi )$ be the point where the unit circle intersects the line between P and the origin O .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] So the projections of the intersection point $P'$ of the line $OP$ with the unit circle on the *x*- and *y*-axes are simply $\operatorname {cn} (u,m)$ and $\operatorname {sn} (u,m)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] These projections may be interpreted as 'definition as trigonometry'.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The latter relations for the *x*- and *y*-coordinates of points on the unit ellipse may be considered as generalization of the relations $x=\cos \varphi$ and $y=\sin \varphi$ for the coordinates of points on the unit circle.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The following table summarizes the expressions for all Jacobi elliptic functions pq(u,m) in the variables (*x*,*y*,*r*) and (*φ*,dn) with ${\textstyle r={\sqrt {x^{2}+y^{2}}}}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Equivalently, Jacobi's elliptic functions can be defined in terms of the theta functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the book, they place an additional restriction on m (that $m\notin (-\infty ,0)\cup (1,\infty )$ ), but it is in fact not a necessary restriction (see the Cox reference).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Also, if $m=0$ or $m=1$ , the Jacobi elliptic functions degenerate to non-elliptic functions which is described below.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Simplifications of complicated products of the Jacobi elliptic functions are often made easier using these identities.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The Jacobi imaginary transformations relate various functions of the imaginary variable *i u* or, equivalently, relations between various values of the *m* parameter.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Using the multiplication rule, all other functions may be expressed in terms of the above three.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The transformations may be generally written as $\operatorname {pq} (u,m)=\gamma _{\operatorname {pq} }\operatorname {pq} '(i\,u,1\!-\!m)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The following table gives the $\gamma _{\operatorname {pq} }\operatorname {pq} '(i\,u,1\!-\!m)$ for the specified pq(*u,m*).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Since the hyperbolic trigonometric functions are proportional to the circular trigonometric functions with imaginary arguments, it follows that the Jacobi functions will yield the hyperbolic functions for m=1.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the figure, the Jacobi curve has degenerated to two vertical lines at *x* = 1 and *x* = −1.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The Jacobi real transformations yield expressions for the elliptic functions in terms with alternate values of *m*.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The transformations may be generally written as $\operatorname {pq} (u,m)=\gamma _{\operatorname {pq} }\operatorname {pq} '(k\,u,1/m)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The following table gives the $\gamma _{\operatorname {pq} }\operatorname {pq} '(k\,u,1/m)$ for the specified pq(*u,m*).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Jacobi's real and imaginary transformations can be combined in various ways to yield three more simple transformations.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The real and imaginary transformations are two transformations in a group (D3 or anharmonic group) of six transformations.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] These five transformations, along with the identity transformation (*μ**U*(*m*) = *m*) yield the six-element group.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] where *i* = U, I, IR, R, RI, or RIR, identifying the transformation, γi is a multiplication factor common to these three functions, and the prime indicates the transformed function.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The other nine transformed functions can be built up from the above three.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The reason the cs, ns, ds functions were chosen to represent the transformation is that the other functions will be ratios of these three (except for their inverses) and the multiplication factors will cancel.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The following table lists the multiplication factors for the three ps functions, the transformed *m*'s, and the transformed function names for each of the six transformations.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Thus, for example, we may build the following table for the RIR transformation.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The value of the Jacobi transformations is that any set of Jacobi elliptic functions with any real-valued parameter *m* can be converted into another set for which $0<m\leq 1/2$ and, for real values of *u*, the function values will be real.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] where all the identities are valid for all $u,m\in \mathbb {C}$ such that both sides are well-defined.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] $x^{2}-{\frac {y^{2}}{b^{2}}}=1$ from applying Jacobi's imaginary transformation to the elliptic functions in the above equation for *x* and *y*.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] It follows that we can put $x=\operatorname {dn} (u,1-m),y=\operatorname {sn} (u,1-m)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] So our ellipse has a dual ellipse with m replaced by 1-m.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] This leads to the complex torus mentioned in the Introduction.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Generally, m may be a complex number, but when m is real and m<0, the curve is an ellipse with major axis in the x direction.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] At m=0 the curve is a circle, and for 0<m<1, the curve is an ellipse with major axis in the y direction.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] At *m* = 1, the curve degenerates into two vertical lines at *x* = ±1.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When *m* is complex but not real, *x* or *y* or both are complex and the curve cannot be described on a real *x*-*y* diagram.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] where p and q are any of the letters s, c, d.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the complex plane of the argument *u*, the Jacobi elliptic functions form a repeating pattern of poles (and zeroes).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The residues of the poles all have the same absolute value, differing only in sign.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Each function pq(*u*,*m*) has an "inverse function" (in the multiplicative sense) qp(*u*,*m*) in which the positions of the poles and zeroes are exchanged.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The periods of repetition are generally different in the real and imaginary directions, hence the use of the term "doubly periodic" to describe them.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] where *α* and *β* are any pair of integers.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] *K*(⋅) is the complete elliptic integral of the first kind, also known as the quarter period.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When the factor (−1)*γ* is equal to −1, the equation expresses quasi-periodicity.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When it is equal to unity, it expresses full periodicity.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] It can be seen, for example, that for the entries containing only α when α is even, full periodicity is expressed by the above equation, and the function has full periods of 4*K*(*m*) and 2*iK*(1 − *m*).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Likewise, functions with entries containing only *β* have full periods of 2K(m) and 4*iK*(1 − *m*), while those with α + β have full periods of 4*K*(*m*) and 4*iK*(1 − *m*).
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In the diagram on the right, which plots one repeating unit for each function, indicating phase along with the location of poles and zeroes, a number of regularities can be noted: The inverse of each function is opposite the diagonal, and has the same size unit cell, with poles and zeroes exchanged.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The pole and zero arrangement in the auxiliary rectangle formed by (0,0), (*K*,0), (0,*K*′) and (*K*,*K*′) are in accordance with the description of the pole and zero placement described in the introduction above.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Also, the size of the white ovals indicating poles are a rough measure of the absolute value of the residue for that pole.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] When applicable, poles displaced above by 2*K* or displaced to the right by 2*K*′ have the same value but with signs reversed, while those diagonally opposite have the same value.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Note that poles and zeroes on the left and lower edges are considered part of the unit cell, while those on the upper and right edges are not.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The function $u\mapsto \operatorname {sn} (u,m)$ is the unique elliptic function having simple poles at $2rK+(2s+1)iK'$ (with $r,s\in \mathbb {Z}$ ) with residues $(-1)^{r}/{\sqrt {m}}$ taking the value 0 at 0 .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The function $u\mapsto \operatorname {cn} (u,m)$ is the unique elliptic function having simple poles at $2rK+(2s+1)iK'$ (with $r,s\in \mathbb {Z}$ ) with residues $(-1)^{r+s-1}i/{\sqrt {m}}$ taking the value 1 at 0 .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The function $u\mapsto \operatorname {dn} (u,m)$ is the unique elliptic function having simple poles at $2rK+(2s+1)iK'$ (with $r,s\in \mathbb {Z}$ ) with residues $(-1)^{s-1}i$ taking the value 1 at 0 .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] For the Jacobi amplitude, $\operatorname {am} (u,0)=u$ and $\operatorname {am} (u,1)=\operatorname {gd} u$ where $\operatorname {gd}$ is the Gudermannian function.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In general if neither of p,q is d then $\operatorname {pq} (u,1)=\operatorname {pq} (\operatorname {gd} (u),0)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] To get *x*3, we take the tangent of twice the arctangent of the modulus.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Relations between squares of the functions can be derived from two basic relationships (Arguments (*u*,*m*) suppressed): $\operatorname {cn} ^{2}+\operatorname {sn} ^{2}=1$ $\operatorname {cn} ^{2}+m'\operatorname {sn} ^{2}=\operatorname {dn} ^{2}$ where *m + m'*= 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Using the multiplication rule, other relationships may be derived.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] From this we see that (cn, sn, dn) parametrizes an elliptic curve which is the intersection of the two quadrics defined by the above two equations.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Double angle formulae can be easily derived from the above equations by setting *x* = *y*.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Bivariate power series expansions have been published by Schett.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The theta function ratios provide an efficient way of computing the Jacobi elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] This is notable for its rapid convergence.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] It is then trivial to compute all Jacobi elliptic functions from the Jacobi amplitude $\operatorname {am}$ on the real line.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] In conjunction with the addition theorems for elliptic functions (which hold for complex numbers in general) and the Jacobi transformations, the method of computation described above can be used to compute all Jacobi elliptic functions in the whole complex plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Another method of fast computation of the Jacobi elliptic functions via the arithmetic–geometric mean, avoiding the computation of the Jacobi amplitude, is due to Herbert E.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] Yet, another method for a rapidly converging fast computation of the Jacobi elliptic sine function found in the literature is shown below.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p01] The Jacobi elliptic functions can be expanded in terms of the hyperbolic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p02] The inverses of the Jacobi elliptic functions can be defined similarly to the inverse trigonometric functions; if $x=\operatorname {sn} (\xi ,m)$ , $\xi =\operatorname {arcsn} (x,m)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p02] They can be represented as elliptic integrals, and power series representations have been found.
[src:elliptic-functions/jacobi-elliptic-functions-p02] The Peirce quincuncial projection is a map projection based on Jacobian elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] In mathematics, the **lemniscate elliptic functions** are elliptic functions related to the arc length of the lemniscate of Bernoulli.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] They were first studied by Giulio Fagnano in 1718 and later by Leonhard Euler and Carl Friedrich Gauss, among others.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The **lemniscate sine** and **lemniscate cosine** functions, usually written with the symbols sl and cl (sometimes the symbols sinlem and coslem or sin lemn and cos lemn are used instead), are analogous to the trigonometric functions sine and cosine.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The lemniscate functions have periods related to a number $\varpi =$ 2.622057... called the lemniscate constant, the ratio of a lemniscate's perimeter to its diameter.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] This number is a quartic analog of the (quadratic) $\pi =$ 3.141592..., ratio of perimeter to diameter of a circle.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The lemniscate functions and the hyperbolic lemniscate functions are related to the Weierstrass elliptic function $\wp (z;a,0)$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Beyond that square, the functions can be extended to the complex plane via analytic continuation by successive reflections.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The lemniscate constant ⁠ $\varpi$ ⁠ is a close analog of the circle constant ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠, and many identities involving ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠ have analogues involving ⁠ $\varpi$ ⁠, as identities involving the trigonometric functions have analogues involving the lemniscate functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The Machin formula for ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠ is ${\textstyle {\tfrac {1}{4}}\pi =4\arctan {\tfrac {1}{5}}-\arctan {\tfrac {1}{239}},}$ and several similar formulas for ⁠ $\pi$ ⁠ can be developed using trigonometric angle sum identities, e.g.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] As a result, both functions are invariant under translation by an even-Gaussian-integer multiple of $\varpi$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] That is, a displacement $(a+bi)\varpi ,$ with $a+b=2k$ for integers ⁠ a ⁠, ⁠ b ⁠, and ⁠ k ⁠.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] This makes them elliptic functions (doubly periodic meromorphic functions in the complex plane) with a diagonal square period lattice of fundamental periods $(1+i)\varpi$ and $(1-i)\varpi$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Elliptic functions with a square period lattice are more symmetrical than arbitrary elliptic functions, following the symmetries of the square.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The sl function has simple zeros at Gaussian integer multiples of ⁠ $\varpi$ ⁠, complex numbers of the form $a\varpi +b\varpi i$ for integers ⁠ a ⁠ and ⁠ b ⁠.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] It has simple poles at Gaussian half-integer multiples of ⁠ $\varpi$ ⁠, complex numbers of the form ${\bigl (}a+{\tfrac {1}{2}}{\bigr )}\varpi +{\bigl (}b+{\tfrac {1}{2}}{\bigr )}\varpi i$ , with residues $(-1)^{a-b+1}i$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The cl function is reflected and offset from the sl function, $\operatorname {cl} z={\operatorname {sl} }{\bigl (}{\tfrac {1}{2}}\varpi -z{\bigr )}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The last formula is a special case of complex multiplication.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Analogous formulas can be given for $\operatorname {sl} ((n+mi)z)$ where $n+mi$ is any Gaussian integer – the function $\operatorname {sl}$ has complex multiplication by $\mathbb {Z} [i]$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Like the trigonometric functions, the lemniscate functions satisfy argument sum and difference identities.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The derivative and Pythagorean-like identities can be used to rework the identity used by Fagano in terms of sl and cl.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] where $u,v\in \mathbb {C}$ such that both sides are well-defined.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Note the "reverse symmetry" of the coefficients of numerator and denominator of $\operatorname {sl} 3x$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] This phenomenon can be observed in multiplication formulas for $\operatorname {sl} \beta x$ where $\beta =m+ni$ whenever $m,n\in \mathbb {Z}$ and $m+n$ is odd.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Examples of $\beta$ -torsion generators include $2\varpi /\beta$ and $(1+i)\varpi /\beta$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The polynomial $\Lambda _{\beta }(x)\in {\mathcal {O}}[x]$ is called the $\beta$ -th **lemnatomic polynomial**.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The $\beta$ -th lemnatomic polynomial $\Lambda _{\beta }(x)$ is the minimal polynomial of $\operatorname {sl} \delta _{\beta }$ in $K[x]$ .
