[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] ${\mathcal {L}}$ , the lemniscate of Bernoulli with unit distance from its center to its furthest point (i.e. with unit "half-width"), is essential in the theory of the lemniscate elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The perimeter of ${\mathcal {L}}$ is $2\varpi$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] The points on ${\mathcal {L}}$ at distance r from the origin are the intersections of the circle $x^{2}+y^{2}=r^{2}$ and the hyperbola $x^{2}-y^{2}=r^{4}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p01] Or in the inverse direction, the lemniscate sine and cosine functions give the distance from the origin as functions of arc length from the origin and the point $(1,0)$ , respectively.
