[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] The functions $\operatorname {slh}$ and $\operatorname {clh}$ have a square period lattice with fundamental periods $\{\sigma ,\sigma i\}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] In a quartic Fermat curve $x^{4}+y^{4}=1$ (sometimes called a squircle) the hyperbolic lemniscate sine and cosine are analogous to the tangent and cotangent functions in a unit circle $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ (the quadratic Fermat curve).
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] If the origin and a point on the curve are connected to each other by a line ⁠ L ⁠, the hyperbolic lemniscate sine of twice the enclosed area between this line and the x-axis is the y-coordinate of the intersection of ⁠ L ⁠ with the line $x=1$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] Just as $\pi$ is the area enclosed by the circle $x^{2}+y^{2}=1$ , the area enclosed by the squircle $x^{4}+y^{4}=1$ is $\sigma$ .
