[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] In algebraic number theory, every finite abelian extension of the Gaussian rationals $\mathbb {Q} (i)$ is a subfield of $\mathbb {Q} (i,\omega _{n})$ for some positive integer n .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] This is analogous to the Kronecker–Weber theorem for the rational numbers $\mathbb {Q}$ which is based on division of the circle – in particular, every finite abelian extension of $\mathbb {Q}$ is a subfield of $\mathbb {Q} (\zeta _{n})$ for some positive integer n .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] Both are special cases of Kronecker's Jugendtraum, which became Hilbert's twelfth problem.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] The field $\mathbb {Q} (i,\operatorname {sl} (\varpi /n))$ (for positive odd n ) is the extension of $\mathbb {Q} (i)$ generated by the x - and y -coordinates of the $(1+i)n$ -torsion points on the elliptic curve $y^{2}=4x^{3}+x$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] where $\zeta$ is the Riemann zeta function.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] The **Hurwitz numbers** $\mathrm {H} _{n},$ named after Adolf Hurwitz, are the "lemniscate analogs" of the Bernoulli numbers.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] where $\zeta (\cdot ;1/4,0)$ is the Weierstrass zeta function with lattice invariants $1/4$ and 0 .
