[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] The Peirce quincuncial projection, designed by Charles Sanders Peirce of the US Coast Survey in the 1870s, is a world map projection based on the inverse lemniscate sine of stereographically projected points (treated as complex numbers).
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] When lines of constant real or imaginary part are projected onto the complex plane via the hyperbolic lemniscate sine, and thence stereographically projected onto the sphere (see Riemann sphere), the resulting curves are spherical conics, the spherical analog of planar ellipses and hyperbolas.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] Thus the lemniscate functions (and more generally, the Jacobi elliptic functions) provide a parametrization for spherical conics.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] A conformal map projection from the globe onto the 6 square faces of a cube can also be defined using the lemniscate functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/lemniscate-elliptic-functions-p02] Because many partial differential equations can be effectively solved by conformal mapping, this map from sphere to cube is convenient for atmospheric modeling.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] In mathematics, the **modular lambda** function λ(τ) is a highly symmetric holomorphic function on the complex upper half-plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] It is invariant under the fractional linear action of the congruence group Γ(2), and generates the function field of the corresponding quotient, i.e., it is a Hauptmodul for the modular curve *X*(2).
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] Over any point τ, its value can be described as a cross ratio of the branch points of a ramified double cover of the projective line by the elliptic curve $\mathbb {C} /\langle 1,\tau \rangle$ , where the map is defined as the quotient by the [−1] involution.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] It is the square of the elliptic modulus, that is, $\lambda (\tau )=k^{2}(\tau )$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] In terms of the half-periods of Weierstrass's elliptic functions, let $[\omega _{1},\omega _{2}]$ be a fundamental pair of periods with $\tau ={\frac {\omega _{2}}{\omega _{1}}}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] Since the three half-period values are distinct, this shows that $\lambda$ does not take the value 0 or 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] where K is the complete elliptic integral of the first kind with parameter $m=k^{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] The *modular equation of degree* p (where p is a prime number) is an algebraic equation in $\lambda (p\tau )$ and $\lambda (\tau )$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] Since $\lambda (i)=1/2$ , the modular equations can be used to give algebraic values of $\lambda (pi)$ for any prime p .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] where $\operatorname {sl}$ is the lemniscate sine and $\varpi$ is the lemniscate constant.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] $K(\lambda ^{*}(x))$ and $E(\lambda ^{*}(x))$ (the complete elliptic integral of the second kind) can be expressed in closed form in terms of the gamma function for any $x\in \mathbb {Q} ^{+}$ , as Selberg and Chowla proved in 1949.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] where $\operatorname {dn}$ is the Jacobi elliptic function delta amplitudinis with modulus k .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] where $n\in \mathbb {N}$ and $\operatorname {sn}$ is the Jacobi elliptic function sinus amplitudinis with modulus k .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] For such n , the class invariants are algebraic numbers.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] The class invariants are very closely related to the Weber modular functions ${\mathfrak {f}}$ and ${\mathfrak {f}}_{1}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] The lambda function is used in the original proof of the Little Picard theorem, that an entire non-constant function on the complex plane cannot omit more than one value.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] This theorem was proved by Picard in 1879.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] Suppose if possible that *f* is entire and does not take the values 0 and 1.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] Since λ is holomorphic, it has a local holomorphic inverse ω defined away from 0,1,∞.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] By the Monodromy theorem this is holomorphic and maps the complex plane **C** to the upper half plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/modular-lambda-function] From this it is easy to construct a holomorphic function from **C** to the unit disc, which by Liouville's theorem must be constant.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] In mathematics, **theta functions** are special functions of several complex variables.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Fundamentally, they are a family of *continuous* functions which encode the behavior of *discrete* multi-dimensional periodic systems, such as crystal lattices or points on a torus.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Because they are smooth, they allow the study and manipulation of discrete combinatorial systems using the tools of analysis.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] and others, including abelian varieties, moduli spaces, quadratic forms, and solitons.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Theta functions in two dimensions are functions of two complex arguments.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] In one choice of parameter, for example, z encodes position on a two-dimensional lattice, and $\tau$ or q encodes the shape of the lattice.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] In higher dimensions, the shape of the lattice is dictated by a matrix; in general, theta functions are parametrized by points in a tube domain inside a complex Lagrangian Grassmannian, namely the Siegel upper half space.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] where z and q are complex numbers and $|q|<1$ so that the sum converges.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] This analytic function can be used to solve a combinatorics problem: in how many different ways can an integer be written as the sum of two squares?
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] This is a generating function where the coefficient of $q^{k}$ represents how many ways there are to write k as a perfect square: when $k=0$ , there is just one way.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] When k is any other perfect square, there are two ways: $n^{2}=(-n)^{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] When k is not a perfect square, there are zero ways.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Collecting terms by exponent, we find that $\theta (0,q)^{2}$ is a generating function where the coefficient of $q^{k}$ counts how many ways there are to write k as the sum of any two squares.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Theta functions occur most commonly in the theory of elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] With respect to one of the complex variables z , a theta function has a property expressing its behavior with respect to the addition of a period of the associated elliptic functions, making it a quasiperiodic function.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Abstractly, this quasiperiodicity comes from the cohomology class of a line bundle on a complex torus, a condition of descent.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] One interpretation of theta functions when dealing with the heat equation is that "a theta function is a special function that describes the evolution of temperature on a segment domain subject to certain boundary conditions".
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Throughout this article, $(e^{\pi i\tau })^{\alpha }$ should be interpreted as $e^{\alpha \pi i\tau }$ (in order to resolve issues of choice of branch).
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] There are several closely related functions called Jacobi theta functions, and many different and incompatible systems of notation for them.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] One **Jacobi theta function** (named after Carl Gustav Jacob Jacobi) is a function defined for two complex variables z and τ, where z can be any complex number and τ is the half-period ratio, confined to the upper half-plane, which means it has a positive imaginary part.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The restriction ensures that it is an absolutely convergent series.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] At fixed τ, this is a Fourier series for a 1-periodic entire function of z.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] For any fixed $\tau$ , the function is an entire function on the complex plane, so by Liouville's theorem, it cannot be doubly periodic in $1,\tau$ unless it is constant, and so the best we can do is to make it periodic in 1 and quasi-periodic in $\tau$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Indeed, since $\left|{\frac {\vartheta (z+a+b\tau ;\tau )}{\vartheta (z;\tau )}}\right|=\exp \left(\pi (b^{2}\Im (\tau )+2b\Im (z))\right)$ and $\Im (\tau )>0$ , the function $\vartheta (z,\tau )$ is unbounded, as required by Liouville's theorem.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] This notation follows Riemann and Mumford; Jacobi's original formulation was in terms of the nome *q* = *e**iπτ* rather than τ.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The above definitions of the Jacobi theta functions are by no means unique.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] See Jacobi theta functions (notational variations) for further discussion.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] If we set *z* = 0 in the above theta functions, we obtain four functions of τ only, defined on the upper half-plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] These functions are called *Theta Nullwert* functions, based on the German term for *zero value* because of the annullation of the left entry in the theta function expression.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Alternatively, we obtain four functions of q only, defined on the unit disk $|q|<1$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] which is the Fermat curve of degree four.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Jacobi's identities describe how theta functions transform under the modular group, which is generated by *τ* ↦ *τ* + 1 and *τ* ↦ −⁠1/*τ*⁠.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Equations for the first transform are easily found since adding one to τ in the exponent has the same effect as adding ⁠1/2⁠ to z (*n* ≡ *n*2 mod 2).
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Instead of expressing the Theta functions in terms of z and τ, we may express them in terms of arguments w and the nome q, where *w* = *e**πiz* and *q* = *e**πiτ*.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] We see that the theta functions can also be defined in terms of w and q, without a direct reference to the exponential function.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] These formulas can, therefore, be used to define the Theta functions over other fields where the exponential function might not be everywhere defined, such as fields of p-adic numbers.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] It can be proven by elementary means, as for instance in Hardy and Wright's *An Introduction to the Theory of Numbers*.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] where ( ; )∞ is the q-Pochhammer symbol and *θ*( ; ) is the q-theta function.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] This form is valid in general but clearly is of particular interest when z is real.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] This formula was discussed in the essay *Square series generating function transformations* by the mathematician Maxie Schmidt from Georgia in Atlanta.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Proper credit for most of these results goes to Ramanujan.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] See Ramanujan's lost notebook and a relevant reference at Euler function.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The Ramanujan results quoted at Euler function plus a few elementary operations give the results below, so they are either in Ramanujan's lost notebook or follow immediately from it.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] With the letter $\varpi$ the Lemniscate constant is represented.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The squares of the three theta zero-value functions with the square function as the inner function are also formed in the pattern of the Pythagorean triples according to the Jacobi identity.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The theta function values from the fifth root of the nome can be represented as a rational combination of the continued fractions R and S and the theta function values from the fifth power of the nome and the nome itself.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] For all real values $t\in \mathbb {R}$ the now mentioned formula is valid.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] The constant $\Phi$ represents the golden ratio number $\Phi ={\tfrac {1}{2}}({\sqrt {5}}+1)$ exactly.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] Also in this case $\Phi ={\tfrac {1}{2}}({\sqrt {5}}+1)$ is Golden ratio number again.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p01] These relations hold for all 0 < *q* < 1.
