[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p02] The regular partition sequence $P(n)$ itself indicates the number of ways in which a positive integer number n can be split into positive integer summands.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p02] And the strict partition sequence $Q(n)$ indicates the number of ways in which such a positive integer number n can be split into positive integer summands such that each summand appears at most once and no summand value occurs repeatedly.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p02] Exactly the same sequence is also generated if in the partition only odd summands are included, but these odd summands may occur more than once.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p02] In the Online Encyclopedia of Integer Sequences (OEIS), the sequence of regular partition numbers $P(n)$ is under the code A000041, the sequence of strict partitions is $Q(n)$ under the code A000009 and the sequence of superpartitions ${\overline {P}}(n)$ under the code A015128.
[src:elliptic-functions/theta-function-p02] All parent partitions from index $n=1$ are even.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In mathematics, the **Weierstrass elliptic functions** are elliptic functions that take a particularly simple form.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This class of functions is also referred to as **℘-functions** and they are usually denoted by the symbol ℘, a uniquely fancy script *p*.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] They play an important role in the theory of elliptic functions, i.e., meromorphic functions that are doubly periodic.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] A ℘-function together with its derivative can be used to parameterize elliptic curves and they generate the field of elliptic functions with respect to a given period lattice.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Yet one still wants to find a way to parameterize it.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In a similar way one can get a parameterization of $C_{g_{2},g_{3}}^{\mathbb {C} }$ by means of the doubly periodic $\wp$ -function and its derivative, namely via $(x,y)=(\wp (z),\wp '(z))$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This parameterization has the domain $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ , which is topologically equivalent to a torus.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] There is another analogy to the trigonometric functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] So the sine function is an inverse function of an integral function.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Elliptic functions are the inverse functions of elliptic integrals.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This invertibility is used in complex analysis to provide a solution to certain nonlinear differential equations satisfying the Painlevé property, i.e., those equations that admit poles as their only movable singularities.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Let $\omega _{1},\omega _{2}\in \mathbb {C}$ be two complex numbers that are linearly independent over $\mathbb {R}$ and let ${\displaystyle \Lambda$ be the period lattice generated by those numbers.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This series converges locally uniformly absolutely in the complex torus $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It is common to use 1 and $\tau$ in the upper half-plane $\mathbb {H$ as generators of the lattice.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Dividing by ${\textstyle \omega _{1}}$ maps the lattice $\mathbb {Z} \omega _{1}+\mathbb {Z} \omega _{2}$ isomorphically onto the lattice $\mathbb {Z} +\mathbb {Z} \tau$ with ${\textstyle \tau ={\tfrac {\omega _{2}}{\omega _{1}}}}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Because $-\tau$ can be substituted for $\tau$ , without loss of generality we can assume $\tau \in \mathbb {H}$ , and then define $\wp (z,\tau ):=\wp (z,1,\tau )$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Since the sum converges absolutely this rearrangement does not change the limit.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Then the $\wp$ -function satisfies the differential equation $\wp '^{2}(z)=4\wp ^{3}(z)-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}.$ This relation can be verified by forming a linear combination of powers of $\wp$ and $\wp '$ to eliminate the pole at $z=0$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This yields an entire elliptic function that has to be constant by Liouville's theorem.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The coefficients of the above differential equation $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ are known as the *invariants*.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Because they depend on the lattice $\Lambda$ they can be viewed as functions in $\omega _{1}$ and $\omega _{2}$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The series expansion suggests that $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ are homogeneous functions of degree $-4$ and $-6$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] If $\omega _{1}$ and $\omega _{2}$ are chosen in such a way that $\operatorname {Im} \left({\tfrac {\omega _{2}}{\omega _{1}}}\right)>0$ , $g_{2}$ and $g_{3}$ can be interpreted as functions on the upper half-plane $\mathbb {H$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The *modular discriminant* $\Delta$ is defined as the discriminant of the characteristic polynomial of the differential equation $\wp '^{2}(z)=4\wp ^{3}(z)-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}$ as follows: $\Delta =g_{2}^{3}-27g_{3}^{2}.$ The discriminant is a modular form of weight $12$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] That is, under the action of the modular group, it transforms as $\Delta \left({\frac {a\tau +b}{c\tau +d}}\right)=\left(c\tau +d\right)^{12}\Delta (\tau )$ where $a,b,d,c\in \mathbb {Z}$ with $ad-bc=1$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Note that $\Delta =(2\pi )^{12}\eta ^{24}$ where $\eta$ is the Dedekind eta function.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] For the Fourier coefficients of $\Delta$ , see Ramanujan tau function.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] $e_{1}$ , $e_{2}$ and $e_{3}$ are the roots of the cubic polynomial $4\wp (z)^{3}-g_{2}\wp (z)-g_{3}$ and are related by the equation: $e_{1}+e_{2}+e_{3}=0.$ Because those roots are distinct the discriminant $\Delta$ does not vanish on the upper half plane.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] For numerical work, it is often convenient to calculate the Weierstrass elliptic function in terms of Jacobi's elliptic functions.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This also provides a very rapid algorithm for computing $\wp (z,\tau )$ .
