[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In this case it is also called an elliptic curve.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Now the map $\varphi$ is bijective and parameterizes the elliptic curve ${\bar {C}}_{g_{2},g_{3}}^{\mathbb {C} }$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] $\mathbb {C} /\Lambda$ is an abelian group and a topological space, equipped with the quotient topology.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It can be shown that every Weierstrass cubic is given in such a way.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The statement that elliptic curves over $\mathbb {Q}$ can be parameterized over $\mathbb {Q}$ , is known as the modularity theorem.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This is an important theorem in number theory.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It was part of Andrew Wiles' proof (1995) of Fermat's Last Theorem.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This can be proven by considering constants $A,B$ such that $\wp '(z)=A\wp (z)+B,\quad \wp '(w)=A\wp (w)+B.$ Then the elliptic function $\wp '(\zeta )-A\wp (\zeta )-B$ has a pole of order three at zero, and therefore three zeros whose sum belongs to $\Lambda$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Two of the zeros are z and w , and thus the third is congruent to $-z-w$ .
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] This can be proven from the addition theorem shown above.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] Any elliptic function f can be expressed as: $f(u)=c\prod _{i=1}^{n}{\frac {\sigma (u-a_{i})}{\sigma (u-b_{i})}}\quad c\in \mathbb {C}$ where $\sigma$ is the Weierstrass sigma function and $a_{i},b_{i}$ are the respective zeros and poles in the period parallelogram.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] The Weierstrass's elliptic function is usually written with a rather special, lower case script letter ℘, which was Weierstrass's own notation introduced in his lectures of 1862–1863.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] It should not be confused with the normal mathematical script letters P: 𝒫 and 𝓅.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In computing, the letter ℘ is available as `\wp` in TeX.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In Unicode the code point is U+2118 ℘ SCRIPT CAPITAL P, with the more correct alias weierstrass elliptic function.
[src:elliptic-functions/weierstrass-elliptic-function] In HTML, it can be escaped as `&weierp;` or `&wp;`.
